Our servers weren't open to the exploit, but the load balancers we use from Amazon were.
No, we haven't been "hacked". But there is a possibility that the #heartbleed exploit could've been used to snoop out your information.
If you logged in to any of our games or websites in the last 24 hours using your username+password I'd recommend you to change your password
All of our services should be up and running again. #heartbleed
We're still working on getting the websites back online. #heartbleed
Auth and session servers are back online. You should be able to log in to Minecraft again. #heartbleed
We're working on an alternative authentication setup while waiting for Amazon to patch their load balancers. Stay tuned! #heartbleed

If you want to try it for yourself. Paste the code into a text editor (Notepad will do), and save the file as CodeMangler.java
So "all you had to do" was to compile the code and run it with the false codes that I gave as arguments.
Because if you feed the result back in to the app it will give you back the original code :)
But… what makes the code magic is that it works both as an "encoder" and a "decoder".
It will then put the result of those operations into a string, reverse it, and print it.
So what the CodeMangler those, is to change the ASCII code of all chars in the code. Odd chars are inc by 1 and even chars are dec by one.
